{"case_id": "case-010-d4-28", "container": "HC2", "pipeline_depth": 4, "message": "12 weeks pregnant, chronic HTN on lisinopril. OB asks about medication change.", "latency_ms": 10303, "llm_calls": 2, "tokens_in": 188, "tokens_out": 230, "cost_usd": 0.0001662, "task_success": true, "abstained": false, "answer": "**Recommendation:**\n\nLisinopril, an angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor, is contraindicated in pregnancy and should be discontinued immediately. ACE inhibitors are associated with significant fetal risks, particularly when used during the second and third trimesters, including fetal renal dysfunction, oligohydramnios, anuria, lung hypoplasia, skeletal malformations, and fetal/neonatal death. While first-trimester exposure may carry a lower risk of these specific severe outcomes, discontinuation is recommended as soon as pregnancy is confirmed due to potential risks and the availability of safer alternatives.\n\nThe patient's antihypertensive regimen should be transitioned to a medication with an established safety profile in pregnancy. Recommended first-line agents for chronic hypertension in pregnancy include labetalol, nifedipine (extended-release), or methyldopa. Close monitoring of maternal blood pressure and fetal well-being is essential during this transition and throughout the remainder of the pregnancy.\n\n**", "tool_calls": 0, "hop_metrics": [{"hop": "vector_ingress", "latency_ms": 3, "llm_calls": 0, "tokens_in": 0, "tokens_out": 0, "tool_calls": 0}, {"hop": "cache_gate", "latency_ms": 0, "llm_calls": 0, "tokens_in": 0, "tokens_out": 0, "tool_calls": 0}, {"hop": "analyze", "latency_ms": 4863, "llm_calls": 1, "tokens_in": 81, "tokens_out": 38, "tool_calls": 0}, {"hop": "writer", "latency_ms": 5432, "llm_calls": 1, "tokens_in": 107, "tokens_out": 192, "tool_calls": 0}], "embed_count": 6, "cache_hit": true, "cache_score": 1.0000001192092896, "variant": "exact_repeat", "error": null}
